<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">with respect to this mountain, which, with every other remarkable or dangerous place on the borders of the lake or the interior Country, has its Genii; to whom they never fail to make a speech when passing, accompanied with a present of tobacco and sometimes their Silver Ornaments.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Negouwatche or Sandy mountain is the scene of many of their fairy tales; some of which are very pretty and attended with a moral; and others equally absurd and Childish &#8211; but all tending to prove their Tartar or Arabian Origin, especially those alluding to the Creation and the Deluge.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The sandy mountain is terminated by a point of red and gray freestone which projects near a mile into the lake and is surrounded with rocks chiefly under water, which would make the doubling of the point very dangerous to canoes but for the extreme clearness of the water by which you are enabled to see them in time to avoid the consequence.  There is not perhaps on the globe a body of water so clear so pure and so light as</p>

